11. Analysis of Results

Although training stability improved, the architecture still exhibited important limitations.

The main issue originates from the use of a global feature vector for full point cloud generation.

Current architecture:

Depth Map
→ Global Feature Vector
→ Fully Connected Decoder
→ Point Cloud

This approach forces the model to learn:

Camera projection geometry
Spatial structure
Perspective relationships
Absolute XYZ coordinates
Point ordering

purely from data.

This creates a difficult optimization problem and limits geometric accuracy.

12. Key Limitation

The fully connected decoder destroys spatial locality.

Depth maps contain structured geometric information, but compressing the entire image into a single latent vector removes important spatial relationships required for accurate 3D reconstruction.

As a result:

geometry quality saturates
point cloud realism is limited
generalization becomes difficult
13. Experimental Conclusion

Experiment 2 successfully demonstrated stable depth-to-point-cloud learning using deep neural networks.

The system was capable of generating coarse pseudo-LiDAR point clouds from depth maps.

However, the experiment also revealed the limitations of direct fully connected point cloud regression architectures.

The results indicate that geometry-aware projection methods are more suitable for high-quality pseudo-LiDAR generation.

14. Future Improvements

The next research direction is to replace direct XYZ prediction with geometric reprojection.

